eason May–September 📅 How many days? 2–3 days sufficient How to Get to Zurich? # By plane: Direct flights from Istanbul available. Zurich Airport is very close to the city — there\u0026rsquo;s a train station on the lower floor, reaching the center in 15 minutes.\nCity transport by train: Zurich\u0026rsquo;s public transport system is one of Europe\u0026rsquo;s best. S-Bahn, trams and buses run to the minute. If you get the Zurich Card, all public transport is included, plus museum discounts.\nCard Duration Price Zurich Card 24 hours 29 CHF Zurich Card 72 hours 56 CHF Places to Visit # 1. Altstadt (Old Town) # When you arrive in Zurich, this should be your first stop. Medieval texture along the Limmat River, narrow cobblestone streets and historic buildings. Most of it can be explored on foot.\n2. Grossmünster Church # Zurich\u0026rsquo;s symbol. A Protestant church from the 12th century, the center of the Reformation movement. If you climb the south tower at 64 meters high, you\u0026rsquo;ll see a panoramic view of the city. Free entry, 5 CHF to climb the tower.\n3. Fraumünster Church # Famous for Marc Chagall\u0026rsquo;s stained glass works. A must-see for art lovers. Just a few minutes\u0026rsquo; walk from Grossmünster.\n4. Bahnhofstrasse # Among the world\u0026rsquo;s most expensive shopping streets. 1.5 km long, stretching from the Central Train Station to Lake Zurich. Even if you don\u0026rsquo;t shop, it\u0026rsquo;s worth a walk — the heart of Swiss banking, the window displays are eye-catching.\nFor chocolate: Laderach or Confiserie Sprüngli — both on this street.\n5. Lindenhof Hill # A small hill reached by 10–15 minutes\u0026rsquo; walk from Bahnhofstrasse. The easiest way to see the city and Limmat River from above. Free, always open.\n6. Lake Zurich (Zürichsee) # The lake stretching to the south of the city, a peaceful resting spot with walking paths and picnic areas. Swimming is also possible in summer — there are free beaches within the city.\n7. Lindt Home of Chocolate # In the Kilchberg district, a bit outside the city. Chocolate museum and factory visit. Unlimited Lindt tasting included. Entry 15 CHF, last entry 17:30.\n8. Uetliberg Mountain # A hill reached by train in 20 minutes. The best spot for a panoramic view of Zurich, the lake and the Alps. Free with the Swiss Travel Pass.\n9. FIFA World Football Museum # For football fans. Interactive exhibitions, trophies and world football history. Entry 24 CHF.\nWhat to Eat in Zurich? # Swiss cuisine can be experienced very differently depending on your budget.\nFood Price Zürcher Geschnetzeltes (veal, mushrooms) 30–45 CHF Rösti (potato dish) 15–25 CHF Fondue (per person) 30–40 CHF Raclette 25–35 CHF Supermarket sandwich 5–8 CHF Budget tip: Getting lunch from Migros or Coop supermarkets saves a lot. Restaurant prices are really very high.\nAccommodation # Zurich central accommodation is expensive but the best areas to base yourself:\nNiederdorf: Historic atmosphere, everything within walking distance Around Old Town: Near Grossmünster Oerlikon: More affordable, close to metro Average per night: 150–300 CHF (look for hostels or Airbnb for budget options)\nBudget Planning # Item Daily estimate Accommodation 100–200 CHF Food (economical) 40–60 CHF Public transport 15–30 CHF (or Zurich Card) Museums 0–30 CHF Total ~155–320 CHF/day Day Trip from Zurich: Basel # If you want to see more than one Swiss city, the train between Zurich and Basel is approximately 55 minutes. In Basel you can walk along the Rhine riverside, visit museums and take photos at the border of 3 countries (Switzerland, Germany, France).\nFrequently Asked Questions # Is English spoken in Zurich? Yes, English is very common in tourist areas. Shops, restaurants, train stations — you won\u0026rsquo;t have any problems.\nHow many days to see Zurich? 2 days is sufficient to comfortably see the city center. Plan 3–4 days if you want to add surrounding trips (Basel, Lucerne).\nAre credit cards accepted in Zurich? Accepted almost everywhere. Cash is rarely needed but keeping a small amount of CHF is useful.\nWhat is the cheapest way to get to Zurich? Follow Pegasus or other airlines\u0026rsquo; campaign periods. Winter months (November–March) are more affordable.\nIs the Lindt chocolate museum in the city center? No, it\u0026rsquo;s in the Kilchberg district, ~20 minutes from the center. Take the S8 train to Kilchberg station, then 10 minutes\u0026rsquo; walk.\n","date":"June 10, 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/en/travel/switzerland-zurich-travel-guide/","section":"Travel Guides","summary":"Zurich, Switzerland’s financial capital, is one of the world’s most expensive cities. But with the right planning, it’s possible to see the city’s best places without burning through your wallet.","title":"Switzerland Zurich Travel Guide | Things to Do, Transport \u0026 Budget (2026)","type":"travel"},{"content":"","date":"10. Januar 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/de/tags/teure-europ%C3%A4ische-st%C3%A4dte/","section":"Tags","summary":"","title":"Teure Europäische Städte","type":"tags"},{"content":"","date":"June 10, 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/en/tags/things-to-do/","section":"Tags","summary":"","title":"Things to Do","type":"tags"},{"content":"","date":"June 10, 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/en/tags/uetliberg/","section":"Tags","summary":"","title":"Uetliberg","type":"tags"},{"content":"","date":"June 10, 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/en/tags/zurich/","section":"Tags","summary":"","title":"Zurich","type":"tags"},{"content":"","date":"10. Januar 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/de/tags/z%C3%BCrich/","section":"Tags","summary":"","title":"Zürich","type":"tags"},{"content":"","date":"June 10, 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/en/tags/zurich-2024/","section":"Tags","summary":"","title":"Zurich 2024","type":"tags"},{"content":"","date":"10. Januar 2024","externalUrl":null,"permalink":"/de/tags/z%C3%BCrich-2024/","section":"Tags",